<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="374" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,785,1380]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,785,810]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">Description.</emphasis>
Antennae setose. Forewings yellowish, rose or red, with two nearly straight oblique lines or rows of small spots and sometimes various melanistic areas.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,785,1380]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,372,852,877]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[390,518,852,877]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 7 – 14" captionStart-1="FIGURES 15 – 16" captionStartId-0="4.[151,264,1860,1883]" captionStartId-1="5.[151,264,740,763]" captionTargetBox-0="[151,1436,193,1834]" captionTargetBox-1="[167,1428,193,717]" captionTargetId-0="figure@4.[151,1436,193,1839]" captionTargetId-1="figure@5.[151,1436,193,719]" captionTargetPageId-0="4" captionTargetPageId-1="5" captionText-0="FIGURES 7 – 14. Lithosiinae moths (7 – 9, 11), their labels (10) and male genitalia (12 – 14). 7 — Paraheliosia rufa (Leech, 1890), male, China, Gansu, Kang Xian; 8 — Paraheliosia rufa ussuriensis (O. Bang-Haas, 1927), male, Russia, Primorskiy Kray, 20 km E from Kirovskiy; 9 – 10 — Paraheliosia novirufa (Fang, 1992), holotype, male (9), China, Zhejiang, Zhoushan, and its labels (10); 11, 12 — Nudina artaxidia (Butler, 1881), male, Russia, Blagoveshchensk; 13 — Paraheliosia elegans (Reich, 1937), holotype, China, Zhejiang, West Tien Mu Shan; 14 — Paraheliosia rufa ussuriensis (O. Bang-Haas, 1927), Russia, Primorskiy Kray, 20 km E from Kirovskiy." captionText-1="FIGURES 15 – 16. Male genitalia. 15 — Paraheliosia rufa (Leech, 1890), China, Gansu, Kang Xian; 16 — Heliosia punctata Fang, 1992, paratype, China, Sichuan, Emeishan." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/224838/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/224839/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">
Fig. 
<number box="[446,518,852,877]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374" value="14.085" valueMax="15.17" valueMin="13.0">13–15</number>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[533,608,852,876]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 19" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1946,1969]" captionTargetBox="[175,1400,832,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[168,1404,823,1919]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 19. Male genitalia of Paraheliosia gen. nov. (17 – 18) and Heliosia punctata Fang, 1992 (19). 17 — Paraheliosia novirufa (Fang, 1992) (from Fang, 1992); 18 — Paraheliosia novirufa (Fang, 1992) (from Fang, 2000); 19 — Heliosia punctata Fang, 1992 (from Fang, 2000)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/224840/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">
17– 
<number box="[579,608,852,876]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
): The genus is best marked my male genitalia structure: uncus straight, slightly curved at apex; valve base with short triangular processes; cucullus membranose; sacculus with a fingerlike apical process; juxta with two apical processes; saccus triangular; aedeagus short, with one or few strong apical spines; vesica with two groups of small spine-like cornuti. In general, uncus, valve, juxta and saccus structure, as well as two groups of small spine-like cornuti on vesica are very similar within the know species of the genus. The most remarkable distinguishing character is a number of strong spines at aedeagus apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="374" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,785,1380]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1068,1093]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">Remarks.</emphasis>
By the wing pattern, the genus is similar to the monotypic 
<taxonomicName authority="Staudinger, 1887" authorityName="Staudinger" authorityYear="1887" box="[991,1275,1068,1093]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Nudina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="374" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[991,1074,1068,1092]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">Nudina</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Staudinger" box="[1082,1275,1068,1093]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374" refString="Staudinger, O. (1887) Neue Arten und Varietaten von Lepidopteren aus dem Amur-Gebiete. In: Romanoff, N. M. (Ed.), Memoires sur les lepidopteres. Vol. 3. M. M. Stassulewitch, St. - Petersbourg, pp. 126 - 232, pls. 6 - 12, 16 - 17." type="book chapter" year="1887">
Staudinger, 
<number box="[1216,1275,1068,1092]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374" value="1887.0">1887</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, with the 
<typeStatus box="[1388,1436,1069,1093]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName authority="Butler, 1881" authorityName="Butler" authorityYear="1881" box="[240,547,1103,1128]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Nudina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="374" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="artaxidia">
<emphasis box="[240,376,1104,1128]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">N. artaxidia</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Butler" box="[392,538,1103,1128]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374" refString="Butler, A. G. (1881) Descriptions of new genera and species of Heterocerous Lepidoptera from Japan. Transactions of the Entomological Society of London, 1881, 1 - 23. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2311.1873. tb 01519. x" type="journal article" year="1881">
Butler, 
<number box="[478,538,1104,1128]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374" value="1881.0">1881</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
; the latter species also have a wide dark band at the fore- and hindwing outer margins (
<figureCitation box="[256,338,1140,1165]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1860,1883]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1834]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,193,1839]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 14. Lithosiinae moths (7 – 9, 11), their labels (10) and male genitalia (12 – 14). 7 — Paraheliosia rufa (Leech, 1890), male, China, Gansu, Kang Xian; 8 — Paraheliosia rufa ussuriensis (O. Bang-Haas, 1927), male, Russia, Primorskiy Kray, 20 km E from Kirovskiy; 9 – 10 — Paraheliosia novirufa (Fang, 1992), holotype, male (9), China, Zhejiang, Zhoushan, and its labels (10); 11, 12 — Nudina artaxidia (Butler, 1881), male, Russia, Blagoveshchensk; 13 — Paraheliosia elegans (Reich, 1937), holotype, China, Zhejiang, West Tien Mu Shan; 14 — Paraheliosia rufa ussuriensis (O. Bang-Haas, 1927), Russia, Primorskiy Kray, 20 km E from Kirovskiy." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/224838/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">
Fig. 
<number box="[309,338,1140,1164]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
). However, the male genitalia of these genera are very different: in 
<taxonomicName box="[1103,1186,1140,1164]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Nudina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="374" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1103,1186,1140,1164]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">Nudina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1201,1283,1140,1165]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1860,1883]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1834]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,193,1839]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 14. Lithosiinae moths (7 – 9, 11), their labels (10) and male genitalia (12 – 14). 7 — Paraheliosia rufa (Leech, 1890), male, China, Gansu, Kang Xian; 8 — Paraheliosia rufa ussuriensis (O. Bang-Haas, 1927), male, Russia, Primorskiy Kray, 20 km E from Kirovskiy; 9 – 10 — Paraheliosia novirufa (Fang, 1992), holotype, male (9), China, Zhejiang, Zhoushan, and its labels (10); 11, 12 — Nudina artaxidia (Butler, 1881), male, Russia, Blagoveshchensk; 13 — Paraheliosia elegans (Reich, 1937), holotype, China, Zhejiang, West Tien Mu Shan; 14 — Paraheliosia rufa ussuriensis (O. Bang-Haas, 1927), Russia, Primorskiy Kray, 20 km E from Kirovskiy." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/224838/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">
Fig. 
<number box="[1254,1283,1140,1164]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
) the sacculus apex has two apical spines, while in the new one it is finger-like; the aedeagus apex in 
<taxonomicName box="[1120,1203,1176,1200]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Nudina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="374" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1120,1203,1176,1200]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">Nudina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with two sclerotized plates, but in 
<taxonomicName box="[300,445,1212,1236]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Paraheliosia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="374" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[300,445,1212,1236]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">Paraheliosia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[451,554,1213,1237]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
it has one or few strong spines. Moreover, presence of two strong apical spines at the juxta apex and basal costal valve processes look to be well marked autapomorphic characters of the new genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="374" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,785,1380]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1319,1344]" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">Etymology.</emphasis>
The generic name consists of two parts: the Greek prefix ‘παρα’ (meaning against), and the genus name 
<taxonomicName box="[218,313,1356,1380]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Heliosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="374" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[218,313,1356,1380]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="374">Heliosia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
